          <text>
                    <body>
                              <pb n="1"/>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">
                                        <placeName>London</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(11)">
                                        <placeName>Sussex Hall</placeName>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(12)">
                                        <date>Feby 17. 1852</date>
                              </p>
                              <p>
                                        <addressee>Rev Isaac Leeser</addressee>
                              </p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(2)">I received with great pleasure your letter<lb/> of
                                        the <date>25th Novr</date> and can assure you that I
                                        esteemed<lb/> it an honor to receive a communication from
                                        one so well known by<lb/> his literary reputation both in
                                                  <placeName>America</placeName> &amp;
                                                  <placeName>England</placeName></p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I can assure you that my business during the<lb/>
                                        months of <date>December</date> &amp; <date>January</date>
                                        occupies so much of my time<lb/> that I am precluded from
                                        attending to any private mat<lb/>ters, and the letter which
                                        I received from my brother in<lb/>
                                        <placeName><sic>Cincinatti</sic></placeName> by the mail
                                        which brought me your favor<lb/> was only answered last
                                        week. This explanation will I<lb/> hope be considered by you
                                        satisfactory, and an<lb/> ample apology for not replying to
                                        you ere this.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I think it better to have to state openly to you
                                        the<lb/> reason why I cannot undertake to <sic>percure</sic>
                                        subscribers<lb/> for your Bible, than to lead you to believe
                                        that I am<lb/> either unwilling or too lazy to attempt to do
                                        so. You<lb/> are aware that <persName>Dr. Berusch</persName>
                                        who is in intimate terms<lb/> with me announced some time
                                        ago his intention<lb/> of publishing a translation of the
                                        Bible, and when it<lb/> was intended to form a committee for
                                        the purpose of<lb/> aiding him pecuniarily in the task I
                                        acted as the<lb/> Honorary Secretary of the same. That plan
                                        being abandon<lb/>ed &amp; the doctor undertaking the task
                                        in his own respon-<lb/>sibility I lent him my assistance in
                                        procuring subscribers<lb/> and the first part of the work
                                        viz the Pentateuch is already<lb/> in the hands of
                                                  600<add>?</add> subscribers I need not tell
                                        you<lb/> that a person on the spot has a great advantage
                                        over<lb/> one living at a distance. <persName>D.
                                                  B</persName> has announced his inten</p>
                              <pb n="2"/>
                              <p>intention of continuing the work and I may add that<lb/> the same
                                        is <add>?</add> at this <add>?</add> by the permission<lb/>
                                        of the marrying committee, <persName>Dr. Berusch</persName>
                                        having been for<lb/> many years connected with the society.
                                        As Secretary<lb/> of the Institution &amp; as a friend of
                                        the doctor, and<lb/> having already interested myself for
                                        the success of<lb/> the work, you will perceive that it
                                        would not<lb/> be possible for me to canvass for subscribers
                                        to your<lb/> Bible, and if I were to do so, you must be
                                        aware<lb/> that the English Jews would give the
                                        preference<lb/> to a work published here, as doubtless the
                                        Americans<lb/> would do &amp; have done to one printed in the<lb/>
                                        <placeName>United States</placeName>. I do not consider that
                                                  <persName>Mrs. <add>?</add></persName><lb/> makes
                                        a good agent for the Occident my brother<lb/> writes that
                                        you informed him that <persName>Mr Franklin</persName><lb/>
                                        had led you to expect great assistance from him<lb/> in the
                                        circulation of the work, but I may say<lb/> that as he was
                                        unable to make his own paper<lb/> succeed it ought not to
                                        surprise you that he<lb/> was unable <del>or perhaps</del>
                                        to procure a <add>?</add> favorable<lb/> reception for
                                        another editors work. I will endeavour<lb/> to procure you
                                        some subscribers for the occident<lb/> but the Jews here do
                                        not like subscribing to<lb/> foreign Journals and when the
                                                  L'Ouivers<add>?</add> was<lb/> first published I
                                        could only procure for him<lb/>
                                        <add>?</add> 2 subscribers &amp; he has only 6 in
                                                  <placeName>London</placeName>.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Yours however being written in our native
                                        tongue<lb/> ought to meet with a better reception, but
                                        as<lb/> the Jews subscribe to the Jewish Chronicle
                                        which<lb/> they like (at least many of them,) altho there
                                        are<lb/> many opinions on the merit of the paper as a<lb/>
                                        literary organ, they are not eager to subscribe</p>
                              <pb n="3"/>
                              <p>for another. I must express my surprise that in the<lb/>
                                        <placeName>United States</placeName> occupied by so many
                                        Jews you can<lb/> not find supporters enough, for the
                                        "Chronicle is<lb/> supported here altho many are very
                                        dissatisfied<lb/> with it.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">I cannot say who was the person who
                                        corres-<lb/>ponded for your paper under the signature of
                                                  <persName>O</persName>.<lb/> I have been often
                                        asked whether I was the<lb/> writer &amp; can assure you
                                        that I was not.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">To reply to your request that I should write
                                        a<lb/> monthly letter for your Journal in the state of<lb/>
                                        Jewish affairs in <placeName>England</placeName>, I will
                                        undertake<lb/> the task with pleasure if you think I can
                                        be<lb/> of any service to you. I should wish to remain<lb/>
                                        incrg—for I do not like as I am holding public<lb/> offices
                                        to write under my name as I might feel<lb/> my opinions
                                                  <sic>obacstled</sic> if therefore you wish<lb/> me
                                        to do as you have requested a letter in reply<lb/> to this
                                        shall have in return my first letter to<lb/> the occident
                                        which I will sign <add>משה</add> that being<lb/> my name in
                                        hebrew.</p>
                              <p rend="indent(1)">Should you ever intend paying us a visit
                                                  <del>in<lb/>this,</del> thinking that a personal
                                        interview with our<lb/> co-religionists in this city, would
                                        lend to give a<lb/> larger circulation to your periodical I
                                        shall be<lb/> most happy to see you &amp; render you every
                                        assistance<lb/> in my power</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">I am</p>
                              <p rend="indent(10)">Dear Sir</p>
                              <p rend="indent(11)">yours Truly</p>
                              <p rend="indent(9)">
                                        <persName role="author">Morris S. Oppenheim</persName>
                              </p>
                              <pb n="4"/>
                              <p>
                                        <persName role="author">Morris S. Oppenheim</persName>
                              </p>
